```{r}
require(readr)
emp_sur<-read_csv('employee_survey_data.csv')
gen_data<-read_csv('general_data.csv')
in_tm<-read_csv('in_time.csv')
mngr_sur<-read_csv('manager_survey_data.csv')
out_tm<-read_csv('out_time.csv')
```



```{r}
str(emp_sur)
```


```{r}
str(gen_data)
```


```{r}
str(in_tm)
```


```{r}
str(mngr_sur)
```

```{r}
str(out_tm)
```

```{r}
colnames(in_tm)[1]<-'EmployeeID'
colnames(out_tm)[1]<-'EmployeeID'
```



```{r}
require(dplyr)
sum(gen_data$EmployeeID %in% emp_sur$EmployeeID)
sum(gen_data$EmployeeID %in% in_tm$EmployeeID)
sum(gen_data$EmployeeID %in% mngr_sur$EmployeeID)
sum(gen_data$EmployeeID %in% out_tm$EmployeeID)


```


```{r}
sum(which(is.na(out_tm)) - which(is.na(in_tm)))
# Every NA in in_time is at the same index as index of every NA in out_time.
# It means, each NA represents that particular employee did not come on respective date.

```


```{r}

# Converting time difference into working hours of each employee on each date
work_hrs <- (out_tm - in_tm)

str(work_hrs)

work_hrs$EmployeeID<-in_tm$EmployeeID
```


```{r}
colSums(is.na(work_hrs))
```

```{r}
work_hrs$leaves<-rowSums(is.na(work_hrs))#shows how many days employee takes leave
```

```{r}
rownames(work_hrs)<-work_hrs$EmployeeID
work_hrs$EmployeeID<-NULL
```







```{r}
# Deriving metrics from timestamp information
work_hrs_tpose <- as.data.frame(t(work_hrs))

```



```{r}
require(tidyr)

work_hrs_tpose <- as.data.frame(sapply(work_hrs_tpose, extract_numeric))

```

```{r}
str(work_hrs_tpose)
```




```{r}
Leaves <- sapply(work_hrs_tpose, function(x) sum(is.na(x)))
Tot_Hrs <- sapply(work_hrs_tpose, sum, na.rm = T)
Avg_Hrs <- sapply(work_hrs_tpose, mean, na.rm = T)
Late_Arr_Early_Dep <- sapply(work_hrs_tpose, function(x) sum(round(x) < 8, na.rm = T))
Did_Overtime <- sapply(work_hrs_tpose, function(x) sum(round(x) > 8, na.rm = T))

```


```{r}
################# 4. MERGING THE DATA #################

employee <- merge(gen_data, emp_sur, by = "EmployeeID")
# No drop in no. of rows. All Employee IDs are same and unique in both datasets.

employee <- merge(employee, mngr_sur, by = "EmployeeID")
# No drop in no. of rows. All Employee IDs are same and unique in both datasets.

employee <- cbind(employee, Leaves, Tot_Hrs, Avg_Hrs, Late_Arr_Early_Dep, Did_Overtime)

```


```{r}
colSums(is.na(employee))

# So, rather than hypothetical imputation, it is better to drop rows with NAs.
employee <- na.omit(employee)

```


```{r}
colSums(is.na(employee))

```

as the data is imbalance that's why SVM doesnot works better as it gives sensitivity of 46% to overcome this problem we use smote technique

```{r}

# Balancing the classes by SMOTE
require(smotefamily)

set.seed(100)
trn.smote <- SMOTE(emp.dum, emp.dum$Attrition)

# Classes are well balanced as compared to orig. data.

```


```{r}
emp.dum <- trn.smote$data

index2 <- sample.split(emp.dum$Attrition, SplitRatio = 0.75)

trn.datasmt <- emp.dum[index2, ]
val.datasmt <- emp.dum[!index2, ]




str(trn.dum)

```


```{r}

# Building SVM model


trn.datasmt$Attrition <- as.factor(trn.datasmt$Attrition)

# Linear
svm_lnr <- svm(Attrition~ ., data = trn.datasmt, kernel = "linear")

```




```{r}
act_arr<-as.factor(val.datasmt$Attrition)

val.datasmt$Attrition <- as.factor(val.datasmt$Attrition)

pred_arr <- predict(svm_lnr, newdata = val.datasmt)

confusionMatrix(pred_arr, act_arr, positive = "1")
```
